\section[Delta LSI Case Study Output]{Delta LSI Case Study Output}
\label{app:delta-lsi}

The following is the full \code{summary()} output of the
\code{LeakDeltaLSI} object returned by \code{delta\_lsi()} when comparing
the naive and guarded case-study pipelines described in Section~\ref{sec:casestudy}. Both fits
share the same batch-blocked fold structure with 20 repeats, enabling paired
repeat-level inference.

\begin{CodeOutput}
Delta LSI Summary
=================
Metric:            auc
Exchangeability:   iid
Inference tier:    A_full_inference
R_eff:             20

Point estimates:
  delta_metric (mean):  0.085
  delta_lsi (Huber):    0.085

Sign-flip test:
  p-value:              < 0.001
\end{CodeOutput}

\noindent
The inference tier is \code{A\_full\_inference} because 20 repeats are
sufficient for the sign-flip randomization test and BCa bootstrap intervals
($\geq 20$ repeats yield tier~A full inference).

\section[Delta LSI Simulation]{Delta LSI Simulation}
\label{app:delta-lsi-sim}

The script \code{paper/run\_delta\_lsi.R} includes a small simulation to
evaluate the power of \code{delta\_lsi()}. The design uses $n = 200$,
$p = 20$, 20 repeats of five-fold CV, and $50$ seeds. The naive pipeline
includes a \code{peek\_norm} leakage feature
($x_{\mathrm{leak}} = y + \varepsilon$, $\varepsilon \sim N(0, 0.3)$),
while the guarded pipeline processes only the original features. Both arms
share the same fold structure, enabling paired inference at tier~A.

The rejection rate was $100.0\%$ at $\alpha = 0.05$, with a mean
$\widehat{\Delta}_{\mathrm{metric}} = 0.1953$---the sign-flip test
reliably detects the leakage-induced performance inflation.

Type~I error calibration is not evaluated by simulation because the
sign-flip test has exact size control by construction: for $R \leq 15$
repeats all $2^R$ sign combinations are enumerated, and for $R > 15$ the
Monte Carlo variant applies the Phipson \& Smyth (2010) correction. When
the per-repeat deltas are truly exchangeable under $H_0$ (i.e., the two
pipelines are identical), the test rejects at exactly the nominal rate. A
non-trivial simulation null---in which the two pipelines differ in some
non-leakage respect---would violate the exchangeability assumption and
conflate calibration with sensitivity to pipeline asymmetry.

Results are stored in \code{paper/sim\_results/delta\_lsi\_sim.rds}.

